AVIAN INFLUENZA (38): ITALY (EMILIA-ROMAGNA) POULTRY, HPAI H7N7, OIE
********************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Mon 2 May 2016
Source: OIE, WAHID [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=20122


Highly pathogenic avian influenza, Italy
----------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 2 May 2016 from Prof. Dr. Romano Marabelli, Chief Veterinary Officer, Secretary General, Ministry of Health, Rome, Italy

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 29 Apr 2016
Date of confirmation of the event: 2 May 2016
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 17 Jan 2015
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: highly pathogenic avian influenza virus
Serotype: H7N7
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks:
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1 (HPAI_ER_2016_1): Ferrara, Portomaggiore, Emilia-Romagna
Date of start of the outbreak: 29 Apr 2016
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Birds / 17 000 / 2000 / 600 / 16 400 / 0
Affected population: Layer hens (free-range/organic)

Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]:
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Birds / 11.76 / 3.53 / 30 / 100
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comment: The positivity regards a commercial farm of layer hens (free-range/organic). Increased mortality rate was reported during the last 2-3 days. A protection zone of 3 km and a surveillance zone of 10 km have been established around the farm, which is under restriction. Depopulation has been completed.

Control measures
Measures applied: disinfection/disinfestations; traceability; stamping out; official disposal of carcasses, by-products and waste; surveillance within containment and/or protection zone; vaccination prohibited; no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: No other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type: Experimental Zooprophylactic Institute (IZSVe), PADOVA (national laboratory)
Species / Test / Test date / Result
Birds / gene sequencing / 2 May 2016 / Positive
Birds / haemagglutination inhinition test(HIT) / 30 Apr 2016 / Positive
Birds / reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction (RT-PCR) / 30 Apr 2016 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The 1st time highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) subtype H7N7 was reported by Italy was in August 2013. For that event, 6 outbreaks were reported in the province of Emilia-Romagna (where the current outbreak is located). The event was resolved on 8 Sep 2013. The final report and map are available at, http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000014110_20130918_152557.pdf

In December 2014, Italy also reported one HPAI outbreak subtype H5N8 in the province of Veneto. The event was resolved on 17 Jan 2015. See final report at, http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_fup_0000017007_20150120_161214.pdf

Information on these events was also published in a previous ProMED posting, see below.

A map of Italy's administrative divisions can be seen at, http://www.nationsonline.org/oneworld/map/italy-political-map.htm. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4197376,75.]
